[normal]In terms of impacts on Link we 
[normal]can confirm the
[normal] following:
[normal]1)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Increased rent arrears[bold]: 
[normal]We expect rent arrears to increase in the future due to the following:
[normal] 
[normal]Link’s current rent arrears remai
[normal]n
[normal] relatively
[normal] steady with no significant increase caused by the introduction of the social size criteria
[normal]. However
[normal] this has only been achieved by significant investment in staff resources to support our affected tenants.  
[normal] 
[normal]2)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Increased transaction costs: [bold]At th
[normal]e current time
[normal],
[normal] 61% of our tenants are on full or partial Housing Benefit, which incurs a negligible bank transaction cost. Under Universal Credit it is anticipated that approximately 80% of UC claimants will have their rent paid directly to them and will 
[normal]then pay this to Link. Assuming that every tenant paid their rent in a single payment each month this will equate to approximately 74,000 bank transactions per annum at an average cost of £0.50 per transaction. We are aware from the DPDP that tenants often
[normal] make a number of smaller payments towards their rent each month as they juggle household budgets to meet other bills. The number of bank transactions and 
[normal]therefore the associated costs are likely to be higher than this. Link 
[normal]has had to increase the number
[normal] of licences to allow staff to accept credit card payments and we expect that the number of required licences will increase further as the demand for this facility increases. There is a cost associated with each licence.
[normal] 
[normal]3)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Increased staff resources:[bold] Support
[normal]ing tenants to manage 
[normal]the various aspects of welfare reform is already proving difficult a
[normal]nd the required resources will increase as further Welfare Reform measures are rolled out. The following activities do/will require additional staff resources:
[normal]4)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Housing (Scotland) Act 1987: [bold]Link must comply with the requirements of the Housing 
[normal](Scotland) 
[normal]Act
[normal] 1987 
[normal]when allocating properties. We are concerned that 
[normal]the requirements of the Act are inconsistent with the under-occupancy legislation
[normal],
[normal] particularly in relation to bedroom size, which 
[normal]prescribes
[normal] that 2 children of the same gender must share a room
[normal] even if it
[normal] may only be suitable for single occupancy.  
[normal]We are
[normal] facing challenges to ensure that our Allocations Policy meets the needs of all of our tenants
[normal] regardless
[normal] 
[normal]of whether or not they 
[normal]receiv
[normal]e
[normal] HB.
[normal] 
[normal]5)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Increased Void Costs and Stock Profiles: [bold]V
[normal]oid costs 
[normal]increase where
[normal] the property available 
[normal]does
[normal] not suit the needs 
[normal]of the 
[normal]prospective tenant who bids for 
[normal]it
[normal]. This is of particular concern in hard
[normal]-
[normal]to
[normal]-
[normal]let areas or where there 
[normal]are
[normal] a limited number of properties of a particular size. 
[normal]We are aware of and concerned at the limited availability of one-bedroom properties availa
[normal]ble
[normal] with a reported shortfall of 20% across Scotland
[normal]. 
[normal]Larkfield
[normal] HA has a stock 
[normal]portfolio
[normal] of 394 properties but only 12 of these are 1 bedroom.
[normal]6)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Business viability:[bold] [bold] 
[normal]In general, there are fears throughout the RSL sector that both lender and credit-rating 
[normal]confidence will be adversely affected by the DWP proposals and this might well have a knock-on effect on the terms and conditions imposed by lenders in future. Link itself will be in the same position as any other goods and services provider i
[normal].
[normal]e
[normal].
[normal] if we don
[normal]’t receive sufficient and appropriate payment for those services from our customers, then we can’t cover costs and viability will be threatened.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Private Sector Leasing:[bold]Link currently manages the largest Private Sector Leasing (PSL) scheme in Scotland on
[normal] behalf of 
[normal]the 
[normal]City of Edinburgh Council and provides temporary accommodation for 1
[normal],
[normal]750 tenants who are deemed to be in priority housing need.
[normal]Tenants housed in temporary accommodation often present with multiple vulnerabilities
[normal] and may have chaotic lifestyles. It is likely that they will not have the ability to manage their finances to pay their rent themselves.  It is unreasonable to expect them to keep control of what rent they owe to which landlord and arrange these payments 
[normal]once their Universal Credit payment is received. 
[normal]Whilst it is understood that consideration will be given by DWP to the tenant’s vulnerabilities in order to make payments of rent to the landlord, we are concerned that the processes and administration requ
[normal]ired to set these up will be onerous on housing staff. It is therefore recommend
[normal]ed
[normal] that the default position for tenants in temporary (private or local authority) accommodation 
[normal]is for them to
[normal] have their rent paid directly to the landlord. 
[normal]As previously noted
[normal],
[normal] tenants accessing temporary accommodation are often extremely vulnerable and may have chaotic lifestyles, thus facing considerable risks to their health and 
[normal]well-being if required to share. In order to be sustainable
[normal],
[normal] the shared tenancies are also likely to require intensive housing management and support from an increased number of specialist staff. There are further concerns that the processes involved in ma
[normal]tching individuals to share will result in delays in securing suitable accommodation and pose significant challenges for staff involved. 
[normal]Temporary accommodation has to be flexible and reactive to homelessness needs
[normal]. I
[normal]f the size criteria restriction is applied, Link 
[normal]is
[normal] likely to be in a position where 
[normal]we are
[normal] unable to house those presenting as homeless
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]We 
[normal]will also see an increase in void periods 
[normal]as
[normal] it would be unreasonable to place people in accommodation they will no
[normal]t be able to afford due to shortfalls in benefit entitlement. It is not feasible to manage temporary accommodation in this way as the need for one
[normal]-
[normal]bedroom properties far outweighs their availability. This is likely to increase homelessness and potentially 
[normal]a return to rough sleeping. It also increases the cost for the provider due to potential increase in void periods.
[normal]A standard rate may not cover the actual costs of delivering the scheme so managing agents will
[normal] withdraw from future provision. We believe that the management fee should be paid based on actual service delivery costs, which are scrutinised as part of the tendering process. The administration, claim processes and uncertainties over payment will pose 
[normal]difficulties for Link.   
[normal]In addition to the specific points raised, our expectation is that the cumulative impacts will likely result in an increase in 
[normal]the 
[normal]cost of providing temporary accommodation due to the additional administration involved, the increa
[normal]sed need for specialist housing staff, the shortage of suitable 
[normal]accommodation and the increase in void periods whilst tenants are matched and suitably-sized accommodation is sourced.
[normal]It is likely to increase the number of legal actions and evictions; due 
[normal]to the increase in arrears it will limit future housing options or consideration for re
[normal]-
[normal]referral to our service. This will lead to an increase in homelessness, more pressure on services, but with greater limitations on what can be offered.
[normal] Also, given the 
[normal]relatively high rents in the scheme and the higher risk of non-payment of rent, landlords’ 
[normal]cashflow
[normal] problems may lead to bankruptcy and resultant further homelessness.
[normal]Landlords have not been willing to accept lower rental offers for larger properties whic
[normal]h would meet the benefit cap so we are left with no alternative but to hand them back, reducing the stock of properties suitable for large families.    
[normal]An example of how a tenant is currently affected by the benefit cap.[bold]1 adult and 5 children in a 4 bedr
[normal]oom property. The household income comprises Income Support £339.46 (includes amounts for the children) and Child Benefit £73.90.
[normal]The total income from benefit for this family is £701.81 per week which includes the Housing Benefit award of £288.46 weekly.
[normal]As the benefit cap amount is £500 weekly for this family, they will have to find £201.81 each week to contribute towards their rent.
[normal]This tenant is seeking employment of 16 hours per week paid at 
[normal]the 
[normal]minimum wage of £6.19 per hour. She would then be entitl
[normal]ed to Working Tax Credit and child care costs of up to £339.87 per week. Child Tax Credits of £271.27 per week, Child Benefit of £73.90 and Housing Benefit of £261.51 per week.
[normal]Total benefit income is £946.55 which is £244.74 more than when solely in recei
[normal]pt of benefit.
[normal] 
[normal]Where are the savings?
[normal]Whilst we appreciate the need to encourage people to access employment, it is likely that the pressure to find and sustain employment when a family is experiencing homelessness will place additional stress on the house
[normal]hold. 
[normal]&#xa0;
